8-Ingredient Chocolate Peanut Butter Ganache Tart by @panaceas_pantry ğŸ’—
.
CRUST.
1 cup almond meal.
1 cup rolled oats.
12 large and soft dates, pitted.
2 Tbsp coconut oil
1 Tbsp maple syrup.
.
Add almond meal and oats to a food processor, and pulse until small crumbs forms. 
2. Add remaining ingredients and pulse till you form a dough. If too dry, add 1-2 more dates. Press dough evenly into a lined tart tin and set aside (mine was 8 inch).
.
GANACHE FILLING.
.
200g vegan dark chocolate (mine was 85%).
1 cup thick coconut milk.
1/4 cup maple syrup.
1/3 cup natural, smooth peanut butter. .
1. Cut chocolate into small chunks and set aside in a large, heat proof bowl. 
2. Add coconut milk and maple syrup to a small saucepan. Heat over medium heat until around 40 degrees Celsius (104F), or just above body temperature. Pour warmed milk over the chocolate, and immediately whisk together until the chocolate melts and you have a creamy ganache. Add peanut butter and whisk through.
3. Pour ganache into tart shell. Set in fridge for a couple of hours, then top with berries (or preferred fruit).
.
To serve: cut gently with a hot knife and serve up with a dollop of coconut yoghurt. #bestofvegan

I feel like a love of brussels sprouts signifies some sort of coming-of-age: the moment when, after a revelatory first bite of roasted or fried brussels sprouts as adults, we realize we've been wrong about these tiny cabbages all along. And now we donâ€™t merely like them, weâ€™re obsessed.

Anyways, hereâ€™s my new favorite way to prepare brussels sprouts: miso-roasted with a dash of wine, sesame oil, and a kick of sriracha.  Iâ€™ve been saving this post for now, just in time for Thanksgiving season! Donâ€™t skimp on the olive oil, salt, or the oven time for thisâ€” you want crackly, crispy caramelized edges (bordering on charred, if youâ€™re like me), a tender and starchy interior, and lip-smacking flavor. Recipe below.
.
.
.
Miso-Roasted Brussels Sprouts
1 lb brussels sprouts
1-2 tbsp olive oil 
2 tbsp white or yellow miso paste
1 tsp white wine or rice wine 
1/2 tsp sriracha 
1 tsp maple syrup
2 tsp toasted sesame oil
kosher salt to taste
1 tbsp toasted sesame seeds, for garnish
.
Preheat oven to 425F and line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Rinse and pat brussels sprouts dry, then trim ends and cut each in half lengthwise. In a large bowl, whisk together olive oil, miso paste, wine, and sriracha. Add brussels sprouts and toss in this mixture to coat, then transfer to a baking pan and arrange pieces in one single layer, cut-side down (donâ€™t overcrowd as the sprouts will steam and become soggy; use two sheet pans if needed). Roast until edges are crispy and caramelized, about 20-25 minutes. Wipe down the remaining sauce in the bowl with a spatula and add roasted sprouts back in, along with the sesame oil and maple syrup. Toss to coat, add salt to taste, toss again, transfer to a serving bowl, sprinkle on sesame seeds, and enjoy immediately.
